They claim that the Establishment has abandoned anti-corruption and democratic ideals while they are responsible for policy growth and development.
They are running on socioeconomic populism by catalysing class war politics, claiming that the masses are bleeding at the feet of big business and capital owners aided by the Establishment. They eloquently describe the problem but fail to offer a solution despite their having been elected to do so.
Suffering
A good number of Kenyans are suffering from the Stockholm syndrome — where hostages or abuse victims bond with their captors or abusers. Voters are falling in love with the architects of grand corruption.
Perpetrators of class wars. Failures in offering fiscal and monetary leadership. This is in conflict with the theory of rational behaviour, which assumes that people would rather take actions that benefit them than those that harm them.
Such captors and abusers deserve contempt.
Kenyans must run away from the binary thinking that the 2022 presidential race is limited to two populist candidates. Visionary public and private sector leaders must present themselves to the electorate lest our country slide into populist leadership.





